#Number of people with zero and non zero mortgage as well as their percentages
cust_without_mortgage = data[data['Mortgage'] == 0]['Mortgage'].count()
cust_with_mortgage = data[data['Mortgage'] > 0]['Mortgage'].count()
total_cust = data['Mortgage'].count()
print('')
print("Summary of customers with and without mortgages")
print('')
print("Customer with Mortgage   : {0} percentage:({1:2.2f}%)".format(cust_with_mortgage, (cust_with_mortgage/total_cust)*100))
print("Customer without Mortgage: {0} percentage:({1:2.2f}%)".format(cust_without_mortgage, (cust_without_mortgage/total_cust)*100))

Findings¶

High correlation between Age and experience
Person Loan showing some strong correlation with Income and to a less extend Average Monthly salary and having a CD Account
People with higher income seemed to get the personal loan
More educated people relatively subscibed the Personal Loan at a higher percentage
People with higher credit cards averages seemed to subscribe to personal loans
CCAvg has a lot of Outliers. Might be better to perhaps consider doing a different model for thoe with outliers if the number of data is much

## function to get confusion matrix in a proper format
def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
    cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

5. Business Understanding¶

Confusion matrix means

True Positive (observed=1,predicted=1):

Predicted that presonal loan should be offered and the customer will accept the loan

False Positive (observed=0,predicted=1):

Predicted that personal loan should be offered and the customer will not accept the loan

True Negative (observed=0,predicted=0):

Predicted that personal loan will not be offered and the customer was not accept the loan

False Negative (observed=1,predicted=0):

Predicted that personal loan will not be offered and the customer would have accepted the loan

Since the bank wants to improve/increase the number of customers who will accept the personal loan offer, we want to reduce False Negatives (FN). If FN is high, then it means the bank would not make as much money from the personal loans as we are predicting that customers who would have accepted the loan offer wouldn't accept it. Recall is therefore an important metric that we want to optimize (i.e. get as much true positives as possible correctly). Our current model has a Recall of 61% so we need to improve it before we can deploy to production.

For the False Positive (FP) case, we are predicting that the customer would accept a personal loan while they would not. This would cause no harm to the bank and they would not be loosing any money.
